Alex mentions other products and services that solve one or a few of those problems already. Apps like Telegram, Meetup, NomadList, Seed Oil Scout, Orange Pill App, Instagram and Trip Advisor all come to mind.

The trouble is, they‚Äôre either good solutions for the one dimension they operate in, or they are more general (like Instagram) and people have found a way to use them to acheive ends for which they‚Äôre not purpose built.

The key with Satlantis is to purpose-build a holistic solution that provides value to people at more than one stage of the travel, lifestyle and nomad journey. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm thinking of it as a ‚Äòsuper app‚Äô despite how much I don‚Äôt like that designation.

The app seeks to enhance travel experiences by making them more relevant, social, and dynamic.
Aleksandar Svetski discusses the
technological and cultural readiness for such 
an app and compared it to the early failures 
of Burbn and Foursquare.
The mobile app is expected to be released in a couple of months, with an early web release available now.
Aleksandar Svetski invited readers to try the early web release and watch a presentation from BTCPrague for more information.

¬†
How & where it all started:
In 2023, I was working on The Spirit of Satoshi - a Bitcoin centric LLM that we built our own dataset for and then trained, along with basic RLHF tools (with lightning payouts). We must have trained at least 30 models, maybe more.
¬†
By the end of the year, I concluded that even though we started to generate some revenue, there wasn‚Äôt really a serious business there. At least not a startup worth investing capital into and scaling.
¬†
Around the same time, a seed of another idea had been planted in my mind via two small events.
1. A friend reached out on Telegram asking if we could train some sort of AI on all the bitcoin-friendly locations around the world to act as a bitcoin-travel-assistant.
2. My wife and I were in Salvador trying to find a good coffee place, and all the high-rated places on Google sucked. We only found a place thanks to a word of mouth referral.
¬†
Robert, (the same friend who reached out to me on Telegram) and I bumped into each other in Salvador, and we realised that the AI assistant was the wrong UX. We figured that people need something more visual. Something more like‚Ä¶.NomadList. This led us to the originally idea which we not-so-creatively called: ‚ÄúBitcoin NomadList.‚Äù
¬†
We adapted the idea over a few iterations into a sort of social network for bitcoiners and nomads called ‚ÄúSatlantis.‚Äù
¬†
‚Ä¶ S stands for Sovereign. So Satlantis = Sovereign Atlantis, or the ‚Äúpromised land‚Äù for Sovereign Individuals.
¬†
Satlantis aims to be a super app for nomads, bitcoiners, remote workers, and sovereign individuals, combining features of NomadList, Meetup, Instagram and TripAdvisor

Hey yes, I bought one for my van in Europe this summer. It's epic. 100mb down/20 up in areas with really crap roaming or 4g (that's the "first world of Western Europe").
No subscription, you just pay the monthly fee (which is for the whole continent) when you need it.

Yes, it would fit into a carry on/backpack. The good thing is that it has everything integrated: wlan router. It takes like 40-50 watts so you can use a strong USB-C charging plug for it or even a powerbank. There is, I think, no official support for the USB-C to the powerplug it needs. I haven't fixed that yet but it would allow you to use a charger you may already have.

So the white power supply unit is not necessarily needed to carry around.

BTCFi has liftoff! üöÄ  sBTC, programmable Bitcoin, now live on Stacks mainnet! üí•

"This development represents a significant shift in Bitcoin's utility. Traditional Bitcoin transactions operate on a simple transfer system, but sBTC introduces smart contract capabilities while maintaining Bitcoin's security model."

(excited to build my dapp/DAO with bridged btc instead of a token)

From @danheld: This is a big step forward in utilizing a more securely bridged Bitcoin on the L2 üëè

Bridged Bitcoin is the Bitcoin that you use on a Bitcoin L2, and how securely that Bitcoin is bridged over matters greatly for defi usage on the L2. 

For those who don't know, sBTC is 1:1 pegged to Bitcoin.  This means for every sBTC created, there‚Äôs an equal amount of Bitcoin securely locked to back it. When you mint sBTC, you send BTC into a secure system. The BTC is unlocked and returned to you when you redeem.

sBTC is secured by the largest pool of signers/validators in an open membership network. And anyone can join this pool of signers.

Note that they are capping initial deposits at 1,000 BTC because they want to make sure everything is working properly, which means there could be risks/a few kinks to iron out. 

Congrats again to the ecosystem!

MSTR nasdaq 100 qqq inclusion info.

The announcement will be made at market close tomorrow. 

The index is then rebalanced at market close on 20th December. 

‚ÄòWeighting‚Äô is the percentage of the index that each company is allocated and this is based on the market cap of each company. The higher the market cap, the higher your allocation. It is estimated that if included MSTR will have an allocation of 0.46% 

Although the Nasdaq 100 itself rebalances annually on the 3rd Friday of every December, the weighting‚Äôs are adjusted quarterly (March,June,September,December) to reflect any market cap changes. So if MSTR‚Äôs market cap continues to rise, then in March they will be given a bigger weighting in the index, also if it falls, it will be given a lower weighting. The ETFs and fund tracking the index will also then have to rebalance to keep their weightings accurate to the index. 

With their initial 0.46% weighting, this is estimated to bring an inflow of around $2.1bn into MSTR. This figure is NOT a weekly, monthly or annual figure, it is the initial inflow of cash from share buys if they are added to the index. Although the Nasdaq itself doesn‚Äôt directly buy shares becuse it‚Äôs just a index, funds and ETFs like QQQ, QQQM, QLD who track the performance of the index all buy shares equal to that of the index weightings. 

If included MSTR can still sell shares ATM between the confirmation and the actual rebalancing. There are no rules against this. 

MSTR is classed as a tech company by multiple classification companies which Nasdaq use to determine sectors. MSTR is currently classed as a tech company by all these companies and so Nasdaq have to class it as a tech company.
